{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "LatencyOptimizedAMP",
    "Title": "Latency-Optimized Adaptive Mixed-Precision Inference for Vision Transformers",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By integrating latency-aware adaptive mixed-precision (AMP) quantization with precision-optimized layer-skipping, we can significantly reduce inference latency and memory usage while maintaining high accuracy for Vision Transformers (ViTs).",
    "Related Work": "Existing works such as AMP-ViT and FlexiQ focus on adaptive mixed-precision quantization to reduce computational and memory demands of ViTs. However, they do not explicitly account for latency optimization during inference. Our proposal builds on these works by incorporating latency-aware metrics and precision-optimized layer-skipping to further enhance efficiency.",
    "Abstract": "Vision transformers (ViTs) have revolutionized computer vision but are computationally expensive, leading to high latency and memory usage. While adaptive mixed-precision (AMP) quantization has shown promise in reducing these demands, it often overlooks latency optimization. This paper introduces Latency-Optimized Adaptive Mixed-Precision (LOAMP), a framework that integrates latency-aware AMP quantization with precision-optimized layer-skipping. LOAMP dynamically adjusts the bit-width of each layer and selectively skips layers based on real-time latency constraints and precision requirements. We evaluate LOAMP on various ViT models and demonstrate significant reductions in inference latency and memory usage while maintaining high accuracy. Our approach is validated on the ImageNet dataset and is shown to outperform state-of-the-art methods in terms of latency-accuracy trade-offs.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. **Latency-Aware AMP Quantization**:\n   - **Dataset**: ImageNet\n   - **Models**: ViT, DeiT, Swin\n   - **Procedure**: Implement latency-aware AMP quantization by periodically collecting statistics on activations and gradients. Use these statistics to dynamically adjust the bit-width of each layer to minimize latency while maintaining accuracy.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics**: Inference latency, memory usage, top-1 and top-5 accuracy.",
      "2. **Precision-Optimized Layer-Skipping**:\n   - **Procedure**: Develop a mechanism to selectively skip layers based on real-time latency constraints and precision requirements. Use a Jacobian-based layer-skipping framework to minimize hidden-state perturbation and enforce strict wall-clock budgets.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics**: Inference latency, memory usage, top-1 and top-5 accuracy.",
      "3. **Combined LOAMP Framework**:\n   - **Procedure**: Integrate latency-aware AMP quantization and precision-optimized layer-skipping into a unified framework. Evaluate the combined framework on the same models and dataset.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics**: Inference latency, memory usage, top-1 and top-5 accuracy.",
      "4. **Ablation Studies**:\n   - **Procedure**: Conduct ablation studies to isolate the contributions of latency-aware AMP quantization and precision-optimized layer-skipping.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics**: Inference latency, memory usage, top-1 and top-5 accuracy."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Complexity of Real-Time Latency Optimization**: The dynamic adjustment of bit-widths and layer-skipping may introduce additional complexity and overhead.\n2. **Generalization to Different Models and Datasets**: The proposed framework may require fine-tuning for different ViT architectures and datasets.\n3. **Hardware Compatibility**: The effectiveness of LOAMP may vary across different hardware platforms due to differences in latency and memory constraints.\n4. **Quantization Error Propagation**: The cumulative effect of quantization errors across layers could impact model accuracy, especially in deep ViT architectures."
  }
}
```
