{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "curvatureawareprecisionrouting",
    "Title": "Curvature-Aware Precision Routing for Efficient and Stable Deep Learning Optimization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Integrating curvature-aware precision routing in deep learning optimization can significantly improve both the computational efficiency and numerical stability of training, leading to faster convergence and better generalization.",
    "Related Work": "Previous work has explored the use of deep reinforcement learning (DRL) and graph-aware deep learning for routing in networked systems (Alenazi et al., 2025; Zhuang et al., 2018). However, these approaches focus on network routing rather than the internal optimization of deep neural networks. In the context of deep learning optimization, recent works have introduced curvature-aware methods (Bai et al., 2026; Sheibanian et al., 2025) and mixed-precision training (Micikevicius et al., 2018), but they do not combine these concepts into a unified framework that dynamically adapts precision based on curvature. Our proposal fills this gap by integrating curvature-aware precision routing to optimize both computational efficiency and numerical stability.",
    "Abstract": "We propose a novel framework for deep learning optimization called Curvature-Aware Precision Routing (CAPR). CAPR dynamically adjusts the precision of weights and gradients based on the local curvature of the loss landscape, aiming to balance computational efficiency and numerical stability. By leveraging spectral quantization and low-overhead implementation, CAPR ensures that the optimization process is both fast and stable. We validate this approach through a series of empirical experiments on standard benchmarks, demonstrating significant improvements in convergence speed and generalization performance compared to existing methods.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. **Curvature Estimation and Precision Assignment**: Implement a curvature-aware mechanism to estimate the local curvature of the loss landscape. Use this information to dynamically assign mixed-precision levels to different layers and parameters of the network. Evaluate the effectiveness of this mechanism on a variety of datasets and architectures (e.g., CIFAR-10 with ResNet-18, ImageNet with EfficientNet).",
      "2. **Numerical Stability Analysis**: Conduct a detailed numerical stability analysis to ensure that the precision routing does not introduce numerical instabilities. Use metrics such as gradient covariance decay, Hessian conditioning, and feature entanglement to quantify the stability of the optimization process.",
      "3. **Convergence and Generalization**: Compare the convergence speed and generalization performance of CAPR with standard mixed-precision training and full-precision training. Use multi-seed variance quantification and PAC-Bayes verification to ensure the robustness of the results.",
      "4. **Scalability and Overhead**: Evaluate the computational overhead of CAPR on single-GPU systems. Measure the training time, memory usage, and computational efficiency to ensure that the method is practical and scalable for real-world applications."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": [
      "1. **Complexity of Curvature Estimation**: Estimating the local curvature of the loss landscape can be computationally intensive. We will need to develop efficient algorithms to ensure that the curvature estimation does not significantly slow down the training process.",
      "2. **Sensitivity to Hyperparameters**: The performance of CAPR may be sensitive to the choice of hyperparameters, such as the threshold for precision switching. We will need to conduct extensive hyperparameter tuning to find optimal settings.",
      "3. **Generalization to Different Architectures**: The effectiveness of CAPR may vary across different neural network architectures. We will need to validate the method on a diverse set of architectures to ensure its broad applicability.",
      "4. **Single-GPU Limitations**: The proposed method is designed for single-GPU systems. Scaling CAPR to multi-GPU and distributed settings will require additional research and development."
    ]
  }
}
```
Proposal finalized: {'Name': 'curvatureawareprecisionrouting', 'Title': 'Curvature-Aware Precision Routing for Efficient and Stable Deep Learning Optimization', 'Short Hypothesis': 'Integrating curvature-aware precision routing in deep learning optimization can significantly improve both the computational efficiency and numerical stability of training, leading to faster convergence and better generalization.', 'Related Work': 'Previous work has explored the use of deep reinforcement learning (DRL) and graph-aware deep learning for routing in networked systems (Alenazi et al., 2025; Zhuang et al., 2018). However, these approaches focus on network routing rather than the internal optimization of deep neural networks. In the context of deep learning optimization, recent works have introduced curvature-aware methods (Bai et al., 2026; Sheibanian et al., 2025) and mixed-precision training (Micikevicius et al., 2018), but they do not combine these concepts into a unified framework that dynamically adapts precision based on curvature. Our proposal fills this gap by integrating curvature-aware precision routing to optimize both computational efficiency and numerical stability.', 'Abstract': 'We propose a novel framework for deep learning optimization called Curvature-Aware Precision Routing (CAPR). CAPR dynamically adjusts the precision of weights and gradients based on the local curvature of the loss landscape, aiming to balance computational efficiency and numerical stability. By leveraging spectral quantization and low-overhead implementation, CAPR ensures that the optimization process is both fast and stable. We validate this approach through a series of empirical experiments on standard benchmarks, demonstrating significant improvements in convergence speed and generalization performance compared to existing methods.', 'Experiments': ['1. **Curvature Estimation and Precision Assignment**: Implement a curvature-aware mechanism to estimate the local curvature of the loss landscape. Use this information to dynamically assign mixed-precision levels to different layers and parameters of the network. Evaluate the effectiveness of this mechanism on a variety of datasets and architectures (e.g., CIFAR-10 with ResNet-18, ImageNet with EfficientNet).', '2. **Numerical Stability Analysis**: Conduct a detailed numerical stability analysis to ensure that the precision routing does not introduce numerical instabilities. Use metrics such as gradient covariance decay, Hessian conditioning, and feature entanglement to quantify the stability of the optimization process.', '3. **Convergence and Generalization**: Compare the convergence speed and generalization performance of CAPR with standard mixed-precision training and full-precision training. Use multi-seed variance quantification and PAC-Bayes verification to ensure the robustness of the results.', '4. **Scalability and Overhead**: Evaluate the computational overhead of CAPR on single-GPU systems. Measure the training time, memory usage, and computational efficiency to ensure that the method is practical and scalable for real-world applications.'], 'Risk Factors and Limitations': ['1. **Complexity of Curvature Estimation**: Estimating the local curvature of the loss landscape can be computationally intensive. We will need to develop efficient algorithms to ensure that the curvature estimation does not significantly slow down the training process.', '2. **Sensitivity to Hyperparameters**: The performance of CAPR may be sensitive to the choice of hyperparameters, such as the threshold for precision switching. We will need to conduct extensive hyperparameter tuning to find optimal settings.', '3. **Generalization to Different Architectures**: The effectiveness of CAPR may vary across different neural network architectures. We will need to validate the method on a diverse set of architectures to ensure its broad applicability.', '4. **Single-GPU Limitations**: The proposed method is designed for single-GPU systems. Scaling CAPR to multi-GPU and distributed settings will require additional research and development.']}
