ement an adaptive mixed-precision quantization scheme that dynamically adjusts the bit-width based on the derived rate-distortion trade-off. Use Fisher information to guide the allocation, ensuring that critical information is prioritized.', '3. **Evaluation on Vision Transformers**: Apply the adaptive quantization scheme to vision transformers (e.g., ViT, DeiT) and evaluate its performance on the ImageNet dataset. Compare the accuracy and efficiency with existing methods like AMP-ViT.', '4. **Evaluation on Large Language Models**: Extend the framework to large language models (e.g., LLaMA) and evaluate its performance on tasks like text generation and classification. Compare the FLOPs reduction and model quality with methods like SNIP.', '5. **Robustness Analysis**: Test the robustness of the adaptive quantization scheme under varying conditions, such as different model architectures, dataset sizes, and task complexities. Analyze the failure modes and provide theoretical insights into the performance guarantees.'], 'Risk Factors and Limitations': ['1. **Complexity of Information Estimators**: Accurate estimation of mutual information and task-relevant distortion can be computationally intensive. We will use efficient estimators and approximate methods to mitigate this issue.', '2. **Generalization to New Models**: The framework may need adjustments for different model architectures and tasks. We will conduct extensive experiments to ensure its generalizability.', '3. **Theoretical Guarantees**: Establishing strong theoretical guarantees for the adaptive bit allocation can be challenging. We will focus on deriving achievable rates and providing empirical validation.', '4. **Hardware Constraints**: While our focus is on information-theoretic principles, practical implementation may be limited by hardware capabilities. We will ensure that our methods are compatible with state-of-the-art GPUs and accelerators.']}
