rate-distortion function for various latent space dimensions. Compare the results with traditional compression methods like PCA and autoencoders.', 'Evaluation Metrics': 'Compression rate, distortion (measured by task-specific metrics like classification accuracy or reconstruction error), and mutual information between the original and compressed latent spaces.'}, {'Description': 'Optimize the rate-distortion trade-off using gradient-based methods.', 'Method': 'Formulate the rate-distortion optimization problem as a constrained optimization task and use gradient-based methods to find the optimal compression parameters. Implement this in a neural network training pipeline to dynamically adjust the compression during training.', 'Evaluation Metrics': 'Optimal compression rate, task performance (e.g., classification accuracy, F1 score), and computational efficiency (e.g., training time, memory usage).'}, {'Description': 'Test the robustness of the compressed latent spaces under distributional shifts.', 'Method': 'Evaluate the performance of the compressed latent spaces on out-of-distribution data and adversarial attacks. Compare the robustness with uncompressed and traditionally compressed latent spaces.', 'Evaluation Metrics': 'Robustness metrics (e.g., adversarial accuracy, out-of-distribution detection performance), and computational overhead.'}], 'Risk Factors and Limitations': ['Estimating mutual information and entropy in high-dimensional spaces can be challenging and may require sophisticated estimators.', 'The optimization of the rate-distortion trade-off may be computationally expensive, especially for large neural networks.', 'The theoretical bounds derived may not always be tight, and practical performance may vary depending on the specific task and data distribution.']}
